included.occupation: Graduate student at University of Michigan (MSI)

included.description:
Collaborating with 3 other interns from the University of Washington and Harvard, we designed a research project to analyze Meaningful Use adoption among physicians in a $400 million revenue rural health system. 

Skills
- Research design
- Qualitative research through interviews with healthcare providers and coded thematic analysis 
- Quantitative research through analysis of Meaningful Use adoption trends
- Presentation to executive and director-level clients

included.title: User Researcher

included.description:
Worked with the Universal Shopping Experience team to provide user research support across multiple projects. Conducted in-person usability sessions, remote usability testing, card sorts, and tree tests, with the goal of improving customer shopping experience across different shopping platforms.

Skills
- Survey design, implementation, and analysis
- Remote card sorts and tree tests
- In-person usability testing
- Synthesis and reporting of usability studies
included.title: User Experience Intern

included.description:
Summer medical informatics intern at the National Library of Medicine (National Institutes of Health) working with Drs. Olivier Bodenreider and Bastien Rance. I developed classification techniques and visualizations for source vocabularies in the Unified Medical Language System (UMLS) based on semantic content. This can provide a framework to support system developers in the selection of appropriate source vocabularies.

Skills
- Statistical analysis
- Network visualizations
- Java
- MySQL
included.title: National Library of Medicine Training Fellow

included.description:
Research scientist for the HEALTH-E team led by Drs. George Demiris and Hilaire Thompson. My research centered on developing methods to integrate and visualize information collected from health monitoring data to support older adults. I led multiple independent projects including surveys, usability studies, interviews, and statistical modeling.

Skills 
- focus groups, interviews
- survey design and analysis
- usability sessions (card sorts, tree tests)
- health visualizations 
- gerontology research
- front-end web development (Javascript, CSS, HTML)
- network analysis
- statistical modeling
included.title: Research Scientist (Consumer Health Informatics)

included.summary:
I completed my Ph.D. in Biomedical and Health Informatics at the University of Washington. There I worked with the HEALTH-E group researching how technology can be used to improve older adult health and wellness. This spanned the domains of HCI, gerontology, and informatics. Prior to that I graduated from Johns Hopkins University where I gained a foundation in quantitative analysis with degrees in Biomedical Engineering (B.S.) and Mathematics (B.S.).

I am currently a user researcher for Amazon Web Services, Inc conducting a wide range of studies to improve the customer's cloud computing experience. I have also been fortunate to intern across various companies in a research or engineering role including Intel, Arcadia Healthcare Solutions, Amazon.com, and the National Institutes of Health. You can find out more about me here: http://thaikwondoe.nfshost.com/.
